C.CURRENTNPCS)\\n\\tself.ThirdMain = {}\\n\\tself.MoveTime = Time\\n\\tif not speed then\\n\\t\\tself.speed = 1\\n\\telse\\n\\t\\tself.speed = speed\\n\\tend\\n\\tself.Range = Range\\n\\tself.Turned = false\\n\\tself.Targets = {}\\n\\tself.Target = nil\\n\\tself.CANSEE = false\\n\\tself.Crouching = false\\n\\tself.Pathing = false\\n\\tself.Tick = tick()\\n\\tself.CurrentAttack = nil\\n\\tif self.NPC:FindFirstChild(\\"AttackPlayers\\") then\\n\\t\\tself.AttackPlayers = true\\n\\telse\\n\\t\\tself.AttackPlayers = false\\n\\tend\\n\\tself.Warning = 0\\n\\tself.Path = game:GetService(\\"PathfindingService\\"):CreatePath(PathfindModule.ReturnPathParams())\\n\\tself.Root = self.NPC.PrimaryPart\\n\\tself.Head = self.NPC.Head\\n\\tself.OGHEADC0 = self.NPC.Torso.Neck.C0\\n\\tself.Ignore = {self.NPC,workspace.Terrain}\\n\\tself.Weapon = nil\\n\\tself.NPCGOAL = nil\\n\\tself.pathFailCount = 0 \\n\\tself.Ping =0\\n\\tself", "upvotes": 3, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 13, "created_at": "2025-12-17T06:06:59.693Z"}
7	devforum	4214192	Questions about Luau VMs, Luau threads, and OS threads	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4214192	Scripting	Conceptual confusion regarding the architectural relationship between Luau VMs, Luau threads (coroutines), and Operating System (OS) worker threads, specifically how they relate to the Task Scheduler and Parallel Luau (Actors).	\N	f	advanced	{task.desynchronize}	{}	f	An AI assistant could help by explaining that Luau threads are 'green threads' (cooperative multitasking) managed by the Roblox Task Scheduler, whereas Actors run in separate VMs that are executed on a pool of OS worker threads during the parallel phase of the engine frame.	161	1	9	2026-01-04 03:59:19.389	2026-01-08 17:05:24.160934	{"views": 161, "content": " I believe that Roblox runs on one main (OS) thread, and there are other worker threads which I assume are also OS threads. \\n Does a VM only handle one thread (1 VM = 1 OS thread)? If so, do games run on a single VM because there’s only one main thread? \\n Do all (non-parallel) scripts run Luau threads that are scheduled to run on the main thread? What about actors, does it create a new VM and therefore use another OS thread everytime to run  task.desynchronize ? Does it even make a new VM? And about “use another OS thread”, it uses the worker threads right? \\n Is a VM is an environment where code is ran? What are threads then, a set of instructions that will be scheduled by the task scheduler under a VM? \\n And for Luau threads vs. OS threads, Luau threads are also considered as subthreads because they merely run under the main (OS) thread right? OS threads are the ones that are actually connected to your hardware right? \\n Am I using the terminology right orr am I missing something? ", "upvotes": 1, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 9, "created_at": "2026-01-04T03:59:19.389Z"}
8	devforum	3768388	Move vehicle relative to player camera	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/3768388	Scripting	Mapping camera-relative movement vectors from a mobile thumbstick to vehicle steering and throttle values using physics-based servos and hinges.	\N	f	intermediate	{PlayerModule,GetMoveVector,ToOrientation,GetPivot,Camera,SetAttribute}	{}	t	An AI agent could provide a vector-based logic solution using the Dot product of the car's RightVector and the MoveVector to determine the exact steer value needed to align the car with the camera's direction.	135	0	10	2025-06-21 16:37:06.858	2026-01-08 17:05:24.597969	{"views": 135, "content": " Basically, I want better mobile support for the vehicle system in my game, so I want the car to be driveable using thumbstick. If you’re facing forward and drag your thumbstick to the right it’ll go to the cameras right (exactly how default roblox character movement works). Right now I have a value called steer, if the value is positive it turns right, negative makes it turn left. \\n I have read quite a few devforum posts on how to do it but I am struggling with implementation. What I’ve tried is get what direction the car should be turned and by how much, depending on the values the thumbstick gives with ControlsModule:GetMoveVector(), add that to the orientation the car started with and then stop steering when it has reached that orientation. But for some reason the car just continues going in a circle. \\n Any help would be greatly appreciated. \\n Current Code: \\n  local Player = game:GetService(\\"Players\\").LocalPlayer\\nlocal PlayerModule = require(Player.PlayerScripts.PlayerModule)\\nlocal Controls = PlayerModule:GetControls()\\nlocal Camera = workspace.CurrentCamera\\nlocal InputVector = Controls:GetMoveVector()\\n\\nif InputVector.Magnitude == 0 then\\n\\treturn Vector3.new()\\nend\\n\\nlocal InputForward = -InputVector.Z\\nlocal InputRight = InputVector.X\\nlocal CameraForwardVector = Camera.CFrame.LookVector\\nlocal CameraRightVector = Camera.CFrame.RightVector\\nlocal MoveVector = ((InputForward * CameraForwardVector) + (InputRight * CameraRightVector)).Unit\\n\\t\\nlocal Car = iFolder.Parent.Parent.Parent:FindFirstChild(\\"ConnectedRC\\").Value\\n\\t\\nlocal CamX, CamY, CamZ = Camera.CFrame.Rotation:ToOrientation()\\nCamX, CamY, CamZ = math.deg(CamX), math.deg(CamY), math.deg(CamZ)\\n\\t\\nlocal CarX, CarY, CarZ = Car:GetPivot().Rotation:ToOrientation()\\nCarX, CarY, CarZ = math.deg(CarX), math.deg(CarY), math.deg(CarZ)\\n\\t\\nlocal RotateBy = MoveVector.X*90\\t\\n\\t\\nif MoveVector then\\n\\tiFolder:SetAttribute(\\"Throttle\\", -MoveVector.Z)\\n\\t\\n\\tif CarX &lt; CamY+RotateBy then\\n\\t\\tiFolder:SetAttribute(\\"Steer\\", -MoveVector.X)\\n\\telse\\n\\t\\tiF", "upvotes": 0, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 10, "created_at": "2025-06-21T16:37:06.858Z"}
9	devforum	4228842	:TeleportAsync TeleportUI?	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4228842	Scripting	Cannot find a way to set a custom teleport screen using TeleportAsync or TeleportOptions on the server.	Use the TeleportService:SetTeleportGui() method within a LocalScript to set the ScreenGui before the teleport occurs, as TeleportOptions does not support UI assignment.	t	beginner	{TeleportService,TeleportAsync,SetTeleportGui,TeleportOptions}	{}	t	An agent could check if the user is trying to set a teleport UI via TeleportOptions and suggest implementing SetTeleportGui in a client-side script instead.	38	2	3	2026-01-08 01:51:04.011	2026-01-08 17:05:28.088312	{"views": 38, "content": " I’m currently converting my :Teleport() functions over to :TeleportAsync(). It’s been pretty easy until I couldn’t find anything on adding a teleport screen. Nothing shows up on TeleportOptions so I’m a bit confused. It’s pretty necessary in my game to create that seamless transition. Is there no way, or am I just being blind or can’t see it somewhere? ", "upvotes": 2, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 3, "created_at": "2026-01-08T01:51:04.011Z"}
10	devforum	4226906	Adding models between parts	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4226906	Scripting	Incorrect placement and orientation of road models between two points, resulting in segments starting at the midpoint instead of being centered on it, along with angular misalignment.	The user corrected the loop logic used to iterate through the points and was advised to use Vector3:Lerp(target, 0.5) to find the exact midpoint and CFrame.lookAt for orientation. They also checked for proper alignment of the model's pivot point.	t	intermediate	{PivotTo,CFrame.new,CFrame.lookAt,Vector3:Lerp}	{}	t	An AI coding agent could generate a standard function that takes two Vector3 positions and a Model, calculates the midpoint using Lerp, creates a CFrame using lookAt, and applies it to the model via PivotTo.	57	1	3	2026-01-07 20:17:37.983	2026-01-08 17:05:29.521443	{"views": 57, "content": " \\n \\n Want to achieve: \\nWant to move a model between two parts and make it orient in the direction between the parts. \\n \\n \\n Issue: \\nThe code places the model edge to the center. \\n \\n \\n This is what i want to do - Create a road passing thru these points. \\nSo i loop on the points from 2 to 12 (excluding start and end). \\nTake the midpoint between current point and previous. \\nSo, if I’m at the start (point 2), calculate the midpoint between point 2 and point 1. \\nAdd the road part at the midpoint. \\nGet the orientation between 2 and 1. \\nOrient the road part to this. \\n This comes up as below. \\n         image  1084×465 44.4 KB         \\n         image  867×541 22.1 KB         \\n The parts are not placed at the exact mid points (not visible here). But it seems the part starts at the midpoint. Also there is a slight angular difference which makes the models not align correctly. \\n \\n Solutions tried: \\nTried search results and AI recommendations. \\n \\n 4: Code used \\nUsed these codes but all had almost the same results. \\n 1 ] \\n  \\tmodel:PivotTo(CFrame.new(midpoint))\\n  \\n 2] \\n  \\tlocal targetCFrame = CFrame.new(currentPos, currentPos + direction)\\n  \\n 3] \\n  \\tlocal targetCFrame = CFrame.new(midpoint, midpoint + direction)\\n  \\n 4] \\n  \\tlocal targetCFrame = CFrame.new(midpoint, pos2)\\n  \\n 5] \\n  \\tlocal targetCFrame = CFrame.lookAt(midpoint, pos2)\\n  \\n After the above methods, the model was pivoted like this. \\n  \\tmodel:PivotTo(targetCFrame)\\t\\n  \\n This lookAt was the most recommended option and it should’ve worked correctly. \\n  local targetCFrame = CFrame.lookAt(midpoint, pos2)\\n  \\n This is what i wanted to achieve. \\n         image  755×583 23.8 KB         \\n(Blue crosshairs are the center of the model as well as the midpoint between the connecting red points.) \\n Any idea on what could be going wrong? Does the PivotTo not consider the center of the Model? ", "upvotes": 1, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 3, "created_at": "2026-01-07T20:17:37.983Z"}
