lectance or 0\\n\\tBullet.Material = Properties.PartProperties.Material or Enum.Material.SmoothPlastic\\n\\n\\tif (game.Players.LocalPlayer.Character.Head.CFrame.Position - workspace.CurrentCamera.CFrame.Position).Magnitude &lt; 1 then\\n\\t\\tBullet.CFrame = ViewModel:WaitForChild(\\"Item\\").Item.CFrame\\n\\telse\\n\\t\\tBullet.CFrame = game.Players.LocalPlayer.Character[\\"Right Arm\\"].CFrame\\n\\tend\\n\\n\\tgame.Debris:AddItem(Bullet, 5)\\n\\n\\tlocal BulletVelocity = Instance.new(\\"BodyVelocity\\", Bullet)\\n\\tBulletVelocity.MaxForce = Vector3.new(math.huge, math.huge, math.huge)\\n\\n\\tif (game.Players.LocalPlayer.Character.Head.CFrame.Position - workspace.CurrentCamera.CFrame.Position).Magnitude &lt; 1 then\\n\\t\\tBulletVelocity.Velocity = workspace.CurrentCamera.CFrame.LookVector * Properties.MainProperties.Speed\\n\\telse\\n\\t\\tBulletVelocity.Velocity = game.Players.LocalPlayer.Character.HumanoidRootPart.CFrame.LookVector * Properties.MainProperties.Speed\\n\\tend\\n\\n\\tlocal Touched = Bullet.Touched:C", "upvotes": 3, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 3, "created_at": "2024-08-21T01:45:51.704Z"}
64	devforum	4224568	GetMarkerReachedSignal (I think) being unreliable with lag	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4224568	Animation	GetMarkerReachedSignal triggers with latency during lag, causing animations to overshoot their intended pause point and resulting in desynchronized gameplay logic.	\N	f	intermediate	{GetMarkerReachedSignal,AdjustSpeed,LoadAnimation,AnimationTrack,Animator,ProximityPrompt}	{}	t	Implement a more robust synchronization method by calculating the exact time of the marker using AnimationTrack:GetTimeOfMarker() and checking the TimePosition property within a RunService.Heartbeat loop to force-stop or pause the animation at the precise frame.	62	1	4	2026-01-07 06:09:31.798	2026-01-08 17:06:33.680654	{"views": 62, "content": " I have an animation of the player holding down a button, and then releasing the button and returning to a regular pose (All in one animation). I’m trying to make it so when the animation reaches a marker (exactly when the hand is pressing the button), it activates all the code for it being pressed (playing sound, pausing the animation to hold the position over the button, etc). However, if the player is lagging, it’s quite inconsistent, like the animation sometimes doesn’t pause in time, leading the hand to be above the button. Even worse, sometimes while you’re still holding down the button, you can turn and look around (you shouldn’t be able to until done with the animation but for some reason the lag lets the player do it anyway). \\n Holding down the button Without Lag: \\n         image  1197×807 89.8 KB         \\nHolding down the button With Lag: \\n         image  1175×802 91.3 KB         \\n Here is my local script that animates it: \\n  local Switch = game.Workspace:WaitForChild(\\"Switch\\")\\nlocal Prompt = Switch:WaitForChild(\\"Base\\"):WaitForChild(\\"ProximityPrompt\\")\\nlocal Folderstuff = game.Workspace:WaitForChild(\\"Folderstuff\\")\\nlocal CameraAnimation = require(game.ReplicatedStorage.CameraAnimator)\\nlocal humanoid = game.Players.LocalPlayer.Character:WaitForChild(\\"Humanoid\\")\\nlocal UserIn = game:GetService(\\"UserInputService\\")\\nlocal allowEnd = false\\nlocal counting = false\\nlocal count = 0\\nlocal MajorWarning = 0\\nlocal Mistake = \\"nothing\\"\\n\\nlocal animator = Switch:WaitForChild(\\"AnimationController\\"):WaitForChild(\\"Animator\\")\\nlocal animObject = Switch:WaitForChild(\\"PressSwitch\\")\\nlocal animTrackSwitchPress = animator:LoadAnimation(animObject)\\n\\nlocal animatorPlayer = game.Workspace:WaitForChild(\\"Folderstuff\\"):WaitForChild(\\"PlayerAnims\\"):WaitForChild(\\"PlayerSwitchPress\\")\\nlocal animTrackSwitch = humanoid:LoadAnimation(animatorPlayer)\\n\\nPrompt.Triggered:Connect(function()\\n\\tallowEnd = false\\n\\thumanoid.WalkSpeed = 0\\n\\tPrompt.Style = Enum.ProximityPromptStyle.Custom\\n\\tworkspace.CurrentCamera.", "upvotes": 1, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 4, "created_at": "2026-01-07T06:09:31.798Z"}
68	devforum	4229018	Is cloning sounds good	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4229018	Audio	Roblox Sound instances do not overlap when played multiple times, requiring cloning or pooling to allow simultaneous playback of the same sound effect.	Clone the Sound instance and its parent container, play it, and utilize game.Debris:AddItem based on the sound's TimeLength to ensure automatic cleanup. Object pooling is suggested for high-frequency sounds to minimize performance impact.	t	intermediate	{Sound,Instance.new,Debris,Clone,TimeLength,Resume}	{}	t	Create a SoundManager module that implements an object pool for frequently used sound effects to avoid the overhead of constant cloning and garbage collection while handling overlap logic automatically.	48	0	2	2026-01-08 02:30:50.343	2026-01-08 17:06:36.184335	{"views": 48, "content": " Since playing a sound twice on Roblox doesn’t overlap, but rather stops the sound and makes it restart, over like two years I’ve made it a habit to clone a short sound that could play twice, and delete it soon after, that way the sound can overlap. I recently made a relatively big game and I noticed that in some videos, some sounds don’t play at all. Is that because of this little technique I do? is this bad for performance? Is it entirely suboptimal and I’m stupid? Oh and I do want to clarify I only do this on the client. ", "upvotes": 0, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 2, "created_at": "2026-01-08T02:30:50.343Z"}
