266	devforum	4220085	How do I allow player to aim with 2 fingers on mobile?	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4220085	Scripting	Implementing dual-finger camera control on mobile where the finger pressing a shoot button can also move the camera, while preventing Roblox from interpreting the second finger as a pinch-to-zoom gesture which locks camera movement.	\N	f	advanced	{GuiButton,Active}	{}	t	Create a custom input handler using UserInputService to track multiple Touch IDs, or provide a modified version of the Roblox PlayerScripts CameraModule that disables the default pinch-to-zoom behavior to allow concurrent touch-based rotation.	49	1	3	2026-01-06 00:34:40.409	2026-01-08 17:10:35.339946	{"views": 49, "content": " For example, on the game Rivals, if you hold your finger on the shoot button, you can use that finger to aim while shooting, OR you can also use a second finger to aim while holding the shoot button with your first finger. \\n I have already tried to implement this by setting the Active property of the GuiButton to false, but when I try to aim with another finger, it does not let me move my camera. I believe this is because roblox detects it as being a pinch to zoom in/out and when you are zooming in/out on mobile, you cannot move your camera up/down/left/right. \\n Also when the Active property of the GuiButton is true, it allows me to aim with my second finger but not my first (the one pressing the shoot button) because when Active is true, the button becomes an input sink. \\n I have looked on other posts but haven’t been able to find a solution to this. Any help would be appreciated! ", "upvotes": 1, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 3, "created_at": "2026-01-06T00:34:40.409Z"}
269	devforum	4227047	I need help with mortor6ds for a camera system thing	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4227047	Scripting	Motor6D camera tracking fails to rotate correctly when the base model is rotated because the script uses global directions instead of local object space coordinates.	Use CFrame:ToObjectSpace() to transform the global 'LookAt' CFrame into the local coordinate system of the camera's base, ensuring the rotation is relative to the model's orientation.	t	intermediate	{TweenService,RunService,Players,CFrame,Motor6D,ToObjectSpace,Heartbeat,Lerp}	{}	t	A coding agent can detect when CFrame calculations for joints (like Motor6D) are done in WorldSpace and suggest using ToObjectSpace to make them orientation-agnostic.	29	1	2	2026-01-07 20:42:07.238	2026-01-08 17:10:38.499336	{"views": 29, "content": " so when the model is untouched the camera is able to look at the player. but when I rotate the camera 90 to 180 degrees the camera doesn’t track the player correctly when you look at it from the front and still tried to track the player as if it wasn’t rotated. is there a way to make it work regardless of the models rotation \\n sadly it’s not letting me provide a video so I’ll use screenshots: \\n zero rotation: \\n         image  355×534 38.5 KB         \\n180 rotation: (the camera will look but mirrored) \\n         image  471×579 49.2 KB         \\n this is the entire script at the moment: \\n  local tweenService = game:GetService(\\"TweenService\\")\\nlocal players = game:GetService(\\"Players\\")\\n\\nlocal tweenInfo = TweenInfo.new(.8,Enum.EasingStyle.Quad,Enum.EasingDirection.Out)\\n\\nlocal s = script.Parent\\nlocal mainCameraHead = s.MainCameraHead.MainCameraHead\\nlocal yAxis = s.Arm.SecondXaxis.YAxis\\nlocal xAxis = s.Arm.ArmContainer.XAxis\\n\\nlocal LookAtPart\\n\\nlocal function FindClosestPlayer()\\n\\tfor _, v in players:GetPlayers() do\\n\\t\\tlocal Character = v.Character\\n\\n\\t\\tif Character then\\n\\t\\t\\tlocal Head = Character:WaitForChild(\\"Head\\")\\n\\n\\t\\t\\tif not LookAtPart then\\n\\t\\t\\t\\tLookAtPart = Head\\n\\t\\t\\telse\\n\\t\\t\\t\\tif (mainCameraHead.Position - LookAtPart.Position).Magnitude &gt; (mainCameraHead.Position - Head.Position).Magnitude then\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tLookAtPart = Head\\n\\t\\t\\t\\tend\\n\\t\\t\\tend\\n\\n\\t\\tend\\n\\tend\\nend\\n\\nwhile true do\\n\\tif LookAtPart then\\n\\t\\tlocal CameraDirectionH = CFrame.new(mainCameraHead.Position,LookAtPart.Position).RightVector\\n\\t\\tlocal CameraDirectionV = CFrame.new(mainCameraHead.Position,LookAtPart.Position).UpVector * -1.5\\n\\t\\tlocal Goal = CFrame.new(-xAxis.C1.Y, _,_) * CFrame.Angles(0, math.asin(CameraDirectionH.z), 0)\\n\\t\\tlocal Goal2 = CFrame.new(_, -yAxis.C1.Y,_) * CFrame.Angles(math.asin(CameraDirectionV.z), 0, 0)\\n\\t\\tlocal Tween = tweenService:Create(xAxis, tweenInfo, {C1 = Goal}):Play()\\n\\t\\t\\n\\t\\tif CameraDirectionV.Y &lt; -1.2 then\\n\\t\\t\\tlocal Tween2 = tweenService:Create(yAxis, tweenInfo, {C1 = Goal2}):Play()\\n\\t\\t\\t--print(\\"breaking.\\")\\n", "upvotes": 1, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 2, "created_at": "2026-01-07T20:42:07.238Z"}
271	devforum	4207467	How would I filter custom emojis	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4207467	Scripting	Custom emoji strings (e.g., :alpha_A:) bypass the Roblox chat filter, allowing users to circumvent language restrictions by spelling out banned words using emoji assets.	Map custom emoji codes to their corresponding alphanumeric characters, filter the translated string using TextService:FilterStringAsync, and check if the result was hashed. If safe, render the original emoji codes; otherwise, block or hash the message.	t	intermediate	{TextService,FilterStringAsync,GetNonChatStringForBroadcastAsync,string.gsub}	{}	t	Create a utility module that accepts an emoji-to-text mapping table and wraps the TextService filtering logic to automatically handle the translation and comparison steps.	165	14	13	2026-01-02 05:10:44.989	2026-01-08 17:10:40.546006	{"views": 165, "content": " \\n cc  @Real_BenTheMiner   @PotatoCommuter  \\n \\n Hello. I am working on a custom chat system for a Roblox game, and it has the functionality to provide users with custom emojis. These work perfectly fine. \\n The game in question, however, is a transit game (Potato City Subway), and we are giving users access to route bullets for better roleplay and interactivity. \\n  \\n   example above \\n The issue is, this flies entirely over roblox’s filter, and inputting swears does not provoke the chat filter at all. We want to give a way for the chat filter to actually recognize these to check for swears and banned words, but we aren’t sure how. \\n It seems nobody else has encountered such a problem, and because we want a vast variety of emojis, a solution has been hard to come by. \\n Any help would be greatly appreciated with this problem. ", "upvotes": 14, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 13, "created_at": "2026-01-02T05:10:44.989Z"}
272	devforum	3005608	What is the UniqueId property?	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/3005608	Scripting	Uncertainty regarding the purpose, accessibility, and origin of the read-only 'UniqueId' property appearing on Roblox instances and its relationship to the Instance API.	The UniqueId is a 32-digit hexadecimal identifier used internally by the Roblox engine and the Instance API for unique instance tracking. It is intentionally read-only and restricted from Luau script access, likely to maintain internal consistency and security during serialization.	t	intermediate	{Instance,UniqueId,"Instance API"}	{}	f	An automated agent can monitor Roblox API dump changes and release notes to provide real-time documentation or alerts when internal properties like UniqueId are exposed or modified.	10250	83	12	2024-06-05 13:08:57.695	2026-01-08 17:10:41.590813	{"views": 10250, "content": " I’ve noticed a new read-only property under all Roblox instances named  UniqueId . This property can’t be accessed through code and is only visible within the object browser. What’s this new property about? Is it a unique identifier that instances use? Is this what the comparison between instances actually compares? Why don’t we have access to it through code? Security reasons? \\n Also when was that added? Are there any announcements related to it? ", "upvotes": 83, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 12, "created_at": "2024-06-05T13:08:57.695Z"}
