369	devforum	4218369	Can Roblox prune Studio-facing data?	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4218369	Networking	Potential performance overhead of Studio-specific properties like .Locked during runtime and the possibility of pruning them to improve replication performance.	Properties have a negligible memory footprint because they are defined only once per-class in reflection. Pruning them is impractical as it would break backward compatibility for developers who reference these properties at runtime, and the engine requires a consistent baseline across all games.	t	intermediate	{Locked}	{}	f	An automated tool could scan codebase for runtime references to Studio-specific properties to determine if they are safe to ignore in a custom build, but it cannot modify how the Roblox engine prunes data during compilation.	147	9	5	2026-01-05 13:46:01.433	2026-01-08 17:12:24.209623	{"views": 147, "content": " I want to know if there exist some properties or information tied to classes, like .Locked, that could be removed when the game is compiled outside of Studio. Or, if Roblox has tried anything like this in the past. \\n I feel like this could improve replication performance, and I don’t know if many use .Locked on runtime outside of Studio testing ", "upvotes": 9, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 5, "created_at": "2026-01-05T13:46:01.433Z"}
372	devforum	4207620	Coroutine.status(thread) continues to return "suspended" if a value is returned in the function	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4207620	Scripting	coroutine.status returns 'suspended' instead of 'dead' when a coroutine returns a value (including explicit nil) after a yield.	Ensure the coroutine returns nothing (use 'return' without arguments or allow the function to end without a return statement) if the intention is for the thread to reach 'dead' status after a yield.	t	intermediate	{coroutine.status,coroutine.create,coroutine.resume,task.wait,task.spawn,task.defer,coroutine.spawn}	{}	t	A coding agent could identify 'return nil' at the end of coroutine bodies following a yielding call and suggest replacing it with a naked 'return' to ensure the thread status updates to 'dead' correctly.	138	3	5	2026-01-02 06:23:45.785	2026-01-08 17:12:27.954829	{"views": 138, "content": " I want to know if this is an intended feature or is it a bug. \\n For some reason if you return any value in the body function of task.spawn / task.defer / coroutine.spawn after a task.wait(), then printing the status of that thread using coroutine.status will always return “suspended”. \\n This will continue to print “suspended” \\n  local thread = coroutine.create(function()\\n\\ttask.wait() -- this is needed to replicate this\\n\\treturn nil -- (any value) end of function, thread should be dead but no\\nend)\\ncoroutine.resume(thread)\\n\\nwhile task.wait(1) do\\n\\tprint(coroutine.status(thread)) -- prints suspended nonetheless\\nend\\n  \\n This will print “dead” \\n  local thread = coroutine.create(function()\\n\\ttask.wait()\\n\\treturn\\nend)\\ncoroutine.resume(thread)\\n\\nwhile task.wait(1) do\\n\\tprint(coroutine.status(thread)) -- prints dead\\nend\\n  ", "upvotes": 3, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 5, "created_at": "2026-01-02T06:23:45.785Z"}
