384	devforum	4219732	UI movement changes with camera lerping	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4219732	Scripting	UI movement speed appears inconsistent due to camera interpolation (lerping) toward a moving target, causing the UI to appear faster or slower depending on the player's vertical movement.	Use frame-rate-independent smoothing for the camera (e.g., 1 - math.exp(-speed * dt)) or hard-set the Camera CFrame to match the target's delta movement, ensuring screen-space UI calculations are decoupled from non-linear camera easing.	t	intermediate	{RenderStepped,UDim2.fromScale,CFrame,Lerp,TweenService:GetValue,CurrentCamera}	{}	t	An AI coding agent can refactor the camera interpolation logic to use exponential decay and suggest calculating UI positions relative to the camera's actual viewport delta rather than a fixed scale increment.	46	0	2	2026-01-05 22:36:10.485	2026-01-08 17:12:40.188397	{"views": 46, "content": " I’m working on a screen effect where a frame generates at the top of the screen and moves down. It’s almost working fine, just that when the player is  moving upwards it’s slower and when they’re moving downwards it’s faster.   Alt view  \\nI’ve tried using offset instead of scale, changing movement intervals, and tweening instead of lerping but nothing changed. Effects have only worked properly when hard shifting the camera without intervals. All help would be appreciated, thank you! \\n  --UI Movement\\nfor i = 1,#Beaming.Objects do --This is inside of a RenderStepped function\\n\\tBeaming.Objects[i].Position += UDim2.fromScale(0,.1*(UIConfig.BeamSpeed*dt))\\n\\n\\tif Beaming.Objects[i].Position.Y.Scale &gt;= 1 + Beaming.Objects[i].Size.Y.Scale then\\n\\t\\tBeaming.Objects[i]:Destroy()\\n\\tend\\nend\\n--Camera Movement, inside RenderStepped function\\nlocal goal = Player.Character.Root.CFrame * CFrame.new(0,PlayerConfig.CameraHeight,0) * CFrame.Angles(-math.pi/2,0,0)\\n\\t\\t\\nif lastPos ~= goal then\\n\\tlastPos = goal\\n\\tstepIndex = dt\\nend\\n\\t\\t\\nlocal a = TS:GetValue(stepIndex,PlayerConfig.CameraEasingStyle,PlayerConfig.CameraEasingyDirection) --Video uses linear\\n\\nworkspace.CurrentCamera.CFrame = workspace.CurrentCamera.CFrame:Lerp(goal,a) --ive also tried math.clamp(stepIndex,dt,1) for a here\\n--workspace.CurrentCamera.CFrame = goal \\n\\t\\t\\nstepIndex += dt\\n  ", "upvotes": 0, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 2, "created_at": "2026-01-05T22:36:10.485Z"}
