482	devforum	4205361	Third Person Camera Glitching	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4205361	Scripting	Third-person character rotation is jittery and glitching when moving in different directions (especially backwards) because of direct CFrame assignment in a render loop without interpolation or disabling default humanoid rotation behavior.	Disable 'Humanoid.AutoRotate' to prevent the engine from fighting the script's rotation, and use 'CFrame:Lerp' to smoothly interpolate the character's orientation toward the camera's forward vector instead of hard-setting the CFrame every frame.	t	intermediate	{RunService,CFrame,UserInputService,TweenService,Humanoid,RaycastParams,PreRender,BindToRenderStep}	{}	t	An automation tool could detect when CFrame is being set directly on a character's PrimaryPart inside a RenderStep/PreRender loop and suggest using Lerp along with setting Humanoid.AutoRotate to false.	88	3	3	2026-01-01 16:53:26.171	2026-01-08 17:14:24.361696	{"views": 88, "content": " I am making a third person, over the shoulder, camera for my game, but how my script is rotating the character is pretty buggy. \\n  \\n    \\nAs you can see and if you try the code out yourself, the character is glitching out when moving in different directions and rotating around, especially when you move backwards.  \\n I want the camera and character to be more smooth and prevent this laggy type of movement. \\n Here is my code: \\n  local Players = game:GetService(\\"Players\\")\\nlocal RunService = game:GetService(\\"RunService\\")\\nlocal UserInputService = game:GetService(\\"UserInputService\\")\\nlocal TweenService = game:GetService(\\"TweenService\\")\\n\\nlocal connection = nil\\nlocal enabled = false\\n\\nlocal player = Players.LocalPlayer\\n\\nlocal character = player.Character or player.CharacterAdded:Wait()\\nlocal camera = workspace.CurrentCamera\\n\\nlocal root = character.PrimaryPart\\n\\nlocal function RotateCharacter()\\n\\n\\tlocal lookVector = camera.CFrame.LookVector\\n\\tlocal flatVector = Vector3.new(lookVector.X, 0, lookVector.Z).Unit\\n\\t\\n\\tlocal targetCFrame = CFrame.new(root.Position, root.Position + flatVector)\\n\\t\\n\\troot.CFrame = targetCFrame\\nend\\n\\nlocal tweenInfo = TweenInfo.new(0.2, Enum.EasingStyle.Quint, Enum.EasingDirection.Out)\\n\\nlocal function TweenOffset(bool)\\n\\t\\n\\tif bool then\\n\\n\\t\\tUserInputService.MouseBehavior = Enum.MouseBehavior.LockCenter\\n\\n\\t\\tlocal tween = TweenService:Create(character.Humanoid, tweenInfo, {CameraOffset = Vector3.new(2, 0.25, 0)})\\n\\t\\ttween:Play()\\n\\t\\t\\n\\t\\tif connection then connection:Disconnect() end \\n\\t\\t\\n\\t\\tconnection = RunService.PreRender:Connect(function()\\n\\t\\t\\t\\n\\t\\t\\tRotateCharacter()\\n\\t\\tend)\\n\\telse\\n\\t\\t\\n\\t\\tUserInputService.MouseBehavior = Enum.MouseBehavior.Default\\n\\n\\t\\tlocal tween = TweenService:Create(character.Humanoid, tweenInfo, {CameraOffset = Vector3.new(0, 0, 0)})\\n\\t\\ttween:Play()\\n\\n\\t\\tif connection then connection:Disconnect() end \\n\\tend\\nend\\n\\nUserInputService.InputBegan:Connect(function(input, processed)\\n\\t\\n\\tif processed then return end\\n\\n\\tif input.KeyCode == Enum.KeyCode.Z then\\n\\t\\t\\n\\t\\tenabled = ", "upvotes": 3, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 3, "created_at": "2026-01-01T16:53:26.171Z"}
464	devforum	4203471	Trouble with type checking	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4203471	Scripting	Circular dependency when sharing Luau types between multiple module scripts that act as classes.	Refactor type definitions into separate modules (e.g., in a ReplicatedStorage/Types folder) that do not contain the class logic, allowing multiple systems to require the types without creating circular dependencies between logic modules.	t	intermediate	{setmetatable,typeof}	{}	t	An automated refactoring tool could extract 'export type' definitions and interface declarations from functional modules into a standalone 'Types' module and update the corresponding 'require' statements.	137	6	7	2026-01-01 01:01:28.727	2026-01-08 17:14:04.557453	{"views": 137, "content": " Before using luau’s type checking, it was hard to sometimes work with big objects that had a bunch of information because the intellisense didn’t always know what type it was supposed to be. When I discovered type annotation it became a lot easier to write code. \\n But it’s gotten to a point where I have multiple module scripts and I want to share types to both but it would cause a circular dependency. I’m not sure if it’s best to combine modules or have a separate module that stores types. Both modules are classes. One of them is to make a spaceship object while the other creates a “Path” object. The path object basically stores methods and info on a path that is being used to generate the spaceship. \\n I’m confused about if there is also a better way to go about this. It feels extreme to have another module to store types which I could just keep in my modules that have those objects. But I also do not want to combine modules as I’m afraid it will get too large and harder to maintain. ", "upvotes": 6, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 7, "created_at": "2026-01-01T01:01:28.727Z"}
