474	devforum	4213101	How do I detect if PlayerRemoving is due to server restart?	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4213101	Scripting	Detecting whether a 'PlayerRemoving' event is triggered by a manual player exit or a server shutdown/restart to prevent unfair win-streak penalties.	Use 'game:BindToClose()' which provides an 'Enum.CloseReason' argument. Since 'PlayerRemoving' fires before 'BindToClose', the server must record the shutdown status (using JobId) and the players present in a DataStore during the 'BindToClose' window. When a player next joins, the system checks the previous session's data to determine if the exit was due to a server restart.	t	intermediate	{PlayerRemoving,BindToClose,Enum.CloseReason,DataStoreService,JobId}	{}	t	A coding agent could generate a boilerplate script that implements a 'Session Reconciliation' pattern: saving player states and JobIds to a DataStore during BindToClose and validating them during PlayerAdded.	85	1	4	2026-01-03 20:40:24.45	2026-01-08 17:14:14.787141	{"views": 85, "content": " I’m trying to detect whether a player left the game due to a server restart. My game is centered around dueling, and players who leave mid-match are punished with losing their win streak, however server restarts run PlayerRemoving before game:BindToClose(), and I’m not sure how to prevent punishing players for server restarts. \\n I’ve already tried game:BindToClose(), storing a variable stating server shut down is true, and then preventing punishing players who are mid-match, however I soon figured out that PlayerRemoving happens before game:BindToClose(), therefore I can’t capture the reason PlayerRemoving happened in the first place. \\n I’ve read more than 5 dev forum posts specifically about this issue, and I can’t find a solution, even with posts that were marked with a solution, and ones specifically about logging and win streaks. I also spent 4 hours attempting solutions and using Roblox’s documentation, without any successful attempts detecting if PlayerRemoving was caused by a server restart. \\n I appreciate any help I can get. ", "upvotes": 1, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 4, "created_at": "2026-01-03T20:40:24.450Z"}
