506	devforum	4214688	Need help with vector force not moving a base part	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4214688	Physics	VectorForce calculation (v-u)/t * m is insufficient to move a character model due to uncompensated friction and potential incorrect time-step (t) usage.	The user identifies that friction between the part and the floor is counteracting the applied force. Potential solutions involve setting PhysicalProperties (Friction) to zero or adding the calculated frictional force into the VectorForce formula.	f	intermediate	{VectorForce,AlignOrientation,AssemblyLinearVelocity,AssemblyMass,PhysicalProperties,RunService.PreSimulation,UserInputService}	{}	t	A coding agent could suggest implementing a PID controller for velocity or automatically adjusting CustomPhysicalProperties to reduce friction. It could also point out that dividing by 1 (t=1) in a high-frequency loop (PreSimulation) results in a very slow acceleration compared to using the actual deltaTime.	70	2	5	2026-01-04 08:04:45.228	2026-01-08 17:14:51.266051	{"views": 70, "content": " I am making my own character movement system, and to move a character, in this case just a simple cylinder, I use  VectorForce  constraint. But the problem I am encountering is that the force that I am calculating, is just too low for the character to move. \\nIf I am not mistaken, then the formula for calculating force is:  (v-u)/t * m  \\n and here’s the code implementation of this: \\n  function Character:PreSimUpdate(deltaTime)\\n    local model = self.__Model\\n    local character: BasePart = model.Character\\n    local camController: CameraController.CameraController = Client.GetInstance().__CameraController\\n    \\n    local camCframe = camController:GetCameraCFrame()\\n    local x, y, z = camCframe:ToEulerAnglesYXZ()\\n\\n    local calculator = CFrame.fromEulerAngles(0,y+math.rad(90),0)\\n\\n    if(UserInputService:IsKeyDown(Enum.KeyCode.D)) then\\n        calculator *= CFrame.new(0,0,1)\\n    end\\n    if(UserInputService:IsKeyDown(Enum.KeyCode.S)) then\\n        calculator *= CFrame.new(-1,0,0)\\n    end\\n    if(UserInputService:IsKeyDown(Enum.KeyCode.A)) then\\n        calculator *= CFrame.new(0,0,-1)\\n    end\\n    if(UserInputService:IsKeyDown(Enum.KeyCode.W)) then\\n        calculator *= CFrame.new(1,0,0)\\n    end\\n\\n    local targetVelocity = Vector3.new(calculator.Position.X, 0, calculator.Position.Z)\\n    if(targetVelocity.Magnitude ~= 0) then\\n        targetVelocity = targetVelocity.Unit * 16\\n    end\\n\\n    character.VectorForce.Force = (targetVelocity - character.AssemblyLinearVelocity)/1 * character.AssemblyMass\\n\\nend\\n  \\n This function is called by  RunService.PreSimulation  event. \\nAs for some reason this force is too low to move the character. I tried multiplying the target velocity by 5 and the thing moves. \\n I am not sure if this is an error on my end or something is up with the  VectorForce  constraint. \\n Adding to this, I also have an  AlignOrientation  constraint in the cylinder that keep it upright, and its  RigidityEnabled  property is set to true. \\n Video demos: \\nWithout multiplying th", "upvotes": 2, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 5, "created_at": "2026-01-04T08:04:45.228Z"}
