550	devforum	4175630	Writing a client based combat system	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4175630	Networking	High network latency and round-trip delay when replicating physics-based knockback using LinearVelocity in a server-authoritative combat system, causing a visible delay between an attack and the victim moving.	\N	f	advanced	{LinearVelocity,SetNetworkOwner}	{}	t	Provide a template for client-side visual extrapolation or prediction where the attacker's client immediately simulates a visual-only knockback on the victim while waiting for the server's official physics update.	273	4	5	2025-12-23 05:21:49.878	2026-01-08 17:15:44.47635	{"views": 273, "content": " Hey, I’m working on a PvP &amp; PvE combat system for a project I’m working on, however I noticed that almost every other fighting game does everything on the server. The user experience becomes significantly worse on anything higher than ~100ms of ping on my side due to input latency. \\n Now for most of these games, I have been researching on how they have their game structured and how it’s been designed and they seem to be running their ability logic on the server – or either on the client, after sending a request to the server and waiting for approval to run it after (which doubles in latency due to the packet having to travel two times just to run the logic). This just doesn’t play well on high ping, but compensates for being fair and mostly cheat-proof, and also look the same to both clients when simulating physics (because the server is the source of truth and also doing the heavy work). \\n I have been leaning towards a combat system with a sort of server authoritative architecture for better responsiveness, but came across a ton of downsides, one of which is how physics look like to the user. For context, here is a pseudocode I came up with that represents the system I have: \\n \\n Every ability will split into two modules: the server side, and client side. \\n The client side ability code runs  immediately  upon input after checking if it can be activated with some client sanity checks, for responsiveness. This is assuming that the server agrees with the client’s decision. \\n When the client side ability code runs, it sends a remote signal to the server for validation, and run server ability code. Two things can happen here:\\n \\n The server agrees with the client, and nothing happens. \\n The server disagrees with the client, and send back a remote signal to that client and rollback to their previous state \\n \\n \\n Every ability can decide their own cooldowns on both client and servers. This makes adding abilities with special inputs easier. \\n An ability ending means that", "upvotes": 4, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 5, "created_at": "2025-12-23T05:21:49.878Z"}
566	devforum	4213106	Having trouble figuring out how to modify AlignOrientations	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4213106	Scripting	Tweening a vehicle to a flat orientation while attempting to preserve its Y-axis rotation (yaw) results in the orientation resetting to (0,0,0) due to incorrect CFrame math and degree-to-radian conversion errors.	\N	f	intermediate	{AlignOrientation,LinearVelocity,TweenService,CFrame,RemoteFunction,SetNetworkOwner,ToOrientation,CFrame.Angles}	{}	t	Correct the landVehicle function logic: CFrame.Angles expects radians, so math.deg(yVal) should not be used. Furthermore, the tween target should be constructed as CFrame.new(base.Position) * CFrame.Angles(0, yVal, 0) to set an absolute orientation rather than multiplying the existing base.CFrame by a relative rotation.	29	0	2	2026-01-03 20:41:51.357	2026-01-08 17:16:00.126082	{"views": 29, "content": " Hello, I’ve been messing around with client-server connections lately to try to make some cool stuff and I’m having issues with align orientations as a result of this. \\n I built a small spaceship that uses align orientation to turn, and when the player gets out of the ship I want the ship to tween to a flat orientation but facing the same Y direction it was facing before flight was canceled. \\n The flight direction I’m handling completely on the client (both linear velocity and align orientation) with the ship’s network ownership being set to the player. I also make it return the last orientation when the player leaves, but for some reason no matter what tween I try it still tweens it to a CFrame angle of 0,0,0. \\n Here’s the code I’m using: \\n  -- Server\\n-- // Assets\\nlocal base = script.Parent\\nlocal controller = script.Controller\\nlocal driver = base.VehicleSeat\\n\\nlocal ao = base.AlignOrientation\\nlocal lv = base.LinearVelocity\\n\\nlocal landConnection = nil\\n\\nlocal function landVehicle(orientation:CFrame)\\t\\n\\tlocal xVal,yVal,zVal = orientation:ToOrientation()\\n\\tlocal yValDeg = math.deg(yVal)\\n\\t\\n\\tlv.VectorVelocity = Vector3.new(0,0,0)\\n\\tTS:Create(base,TweenInfo.new(1,Enum.EasingStyle.Sine),{CFrame = base.CFrame*CFrame.Angles(0,yValDeg,0)}):Play()\\n\\t\\n\\ttask.wait(1.2)\\nend\\n\\nlocal ui = nil\\ndriver.Changed:Connect(function(mode)\\t\\n\\tif mode == \\"Occupant\\" then\\n\\t\\tif ui then\\n\\t\\t\\tlocal orient = ui.GrabLastOrientation:InvokeClient(ui.Parent.Parent)\\n\\t\\t\\t\\n\\t\\t\\tui:Destroy()\\n\\t\\t\\tui = nil\\n\\t\\t\\t\\n\\t\\t\\tbase:SetNetworkOwner(nil)\\n\\t\\t\\tlandVehicle(orient)\\n\\t\\tend\\n\\t\\t\\n\\t\\tlocal occ = driver.Occupant\\n\\t\\tif occ then\\n\\t\\t\\tlocal pl = PLRS:GetPlayerFromCharacter(occ.Parent)\\n\\t\\t\\tif pl then\\n\\t\\t\\t\\tif landConnection then\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tlandConnection:Disconnect()\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tlandConnection = nil\\n\\t\\t\\t\\tend\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\n\\t\\t\\t\\tbase:SetNetworkOwner(pl)\\n\\n\\t\\t\\t\\tui = controller:Clone()\\n\\t\\t\\t\\tui.Vehicle.Value = base\\n\\t\\t\\t\\tui.Parent = pl.PlayerGui\\n\\t\\t\\tend\\n\\t\\tend\\n\\tend\\nend)\\n\\n-- Client\\nlocal base = script.Parent.Vehicle.Value\\nlocal ao = base.AlignOrientation\\nlocal lv = base.LinearVel", "upvotes": 0, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 2, "created_at": "2026-01-03T20:41:51.357Z"}
