568	devforum	4207620	Coroutine.status(thread) continues to return "suspended" if a value is returned in the function	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4207620	Scripting	Coroutines remain in a 'suspended' state instead of 'dead' after execution finishes if an explicit value (including nil) is returned following a yield.	Use a bare 'return' statement without any values, or allow the function to reach its natural end without a return statement, to ensure the thread status becomes 'dead'.	t	intermediate	{coroutine.status,coroutine.create,coroutine.resume,task.wait,task.spawn,task.defer,coroutine.spawn}	{}	t	A static analysis tool or linter could flag explicit return values in functions passed to coroutine or task constructors when the developer likely intends for the thread to terminate.	138	3	5	2026-01-02 06:23:45.785	2026-01-08 17:16:03.092243	{"views": 138, "content": " I want to know if this is an intended feature or is it a bug. \\n For some reason if you return any value in the body function of task.spawn / task.defer / coroutine.spawn after a task.wait(), then printing the status of that thread using coroutine.status will always return “suspended”. \\n This will continue to print “suspended” \\n  local thread = coroutine.create(function()\\n\\ttask.wait() -- this is needed to replicate this\\n\\treturn nil -- (any value) end of function, thread should be dead but no\\nend)\\ncoroutine.resume(thread)\\n\\nwhile task.wait(1) do\\n\\tprint(coroutine.status(thread)) -- prints suspended nonetheless\\nend\\n  \\n This will print “dead” \\n  local thread = coroutine.create(function()\\n\\ttask.wait()\\n\\treturn\\nend)\\ncoroutine.resume(thread)\\n\\nwhile task.wait(1) do\\n\\tprint(coroutine.status(thread)) -- prints dead\\nend\\n  ", "upvotes": 3, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 5, "created_at": "2026-01-02T06:23:45.785Z"}
