778	devforum	3301365	Isometric View and Invisicam..?	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/3301365	Scripting	Customizing the default Roblox Invisicam behavior to achieve partial transparency instead of full invisibility for occluding objects in an isometric camera view.	Fork the Roblox PlayerModule to access and modify the Invisicam sub-module. Specifically, adjust the target transparency constants within the script to a value like 0.5 (instead of the default 1.0) and combine this with a custom isometric camera script using RunService.RenderStepped to maintain a fixed CFrame offset from the character.	t	intermediate	{RunService,RenderStepped,CFrame,Vector3,PlayerModule,Invisicam}	{}	t	An agent could provide the standard Lua code for an isometric camera controller and identify the specific lines in the forked Invisicam script that need to be modified to change the 'TARGET_TRANSPARENCY' variable.	838	0	4	2024-12-11 10:17:30.902	2026-01-08 17:19:45.046228	{"views": 838, "content": " Yesterday as I was scrolling through youtube, I saw this one showcase of a game similar to “Project Zomboid”, I can already figure out that the camera system used is an “Isometric Camera View”, but I still can’t get my head over the invisible wall thing? I read through some posts and it said it was “Invisicam” but as I experimented with it in my Roblox Studio, it doesn’t really give the Project Zomboid Transparency thing as it seems like it made the wall completely invisible and the roofs as well. Any idea on how this one works? \\n     \\n     Screenshot 2024-12-11 171119  1920×1024 227 KB     \\n    ", "upvotes": 0, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 4, "created_at": "2024-12-11T10:17:30.902Z"}
780	devforum	4204219	Handle weld messing / snapping with Motor6D for a second on tool	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4204219	Scripting	A visual glitch or 'snap' occurs for one frame when a tool is equipped because the default RightGrip weld is created before the server-side script can destroy it and replace it with a Motor6D.	\N	f	intermediate	{Motor6D,UserInputService,PlayerService,Humanoid,Animator,RemoteEvent,Tool.Equipped}	{}	t	A coding agent could suggest disabling 'RequiresHandle' to prevent the automatic RightGrip creation or providing a client-side snippet to immediately parent the Motor6D to ensure zero-latency positioning.	70	0	1	2026-01-01 07:58:47.157	2026-01-08 17:19:45.38361	{"views": 70, "content": " Basically, I have a tool that uses a Motor6D for animation, simple stuff. The thing is, I actually have it so the the handle is on the left hand, which has actually exposed a bit of a flaw with this. \\n Basically obviously due to how it works, the motor6d can’t be  literally  instantly overriding the handle weld, so there is a frame where it uses the regular handle weld before getting overridden by the Motor6D. In that frame, the tool looks extremely odd since its not set up to be on that hand, and it really triggers me and I wonder if there is a way to fix this. \\n Here is a video showing what I’m talking about: \\n              \\n \\n And here is my tool’s  client  sided code: \\n  local PlayerService = game:GetService(\\"Players\\")\\nlocal UserInputService = game:GetService(\\"UserInputService\\")\\nlocal tool = script.Parent\\nlocal event = tool:WaitForChild(\\"DrillRigEvent\\")\\nlocal animations = tool.Animations\\nlocal player = PlayerService.LocalPlayer\\nlocal character = player.Character\\nlocal humanoid = character:FindFirstChild(\\"Humanoid\\")\\n\\nlocal idleAnimation = humanoid.Animator:LoadAnimation(animations.DrillRigIdleAnimation)\\n\\nlocal connection = nil\\n\\nlocal function UserInput(input:InputObject,gameProcessedEvent:boolean)\\n\\tif gameProcessedEvent then return end\\nend\\n\\nlocal function Equipped()\\n\\tconnection = UserInputService.InputBegan:Connect(UserInput)\\n\\tidleAnimation:Play()\\n\\tevent:FireServer(\\"SetupMotor\\")\\nend\\n\\nlocal function Unequipped()\\n\\tconnection:Disconnect()\\n\\tidleAnimation:Stop()\\nend\\n\\nlocal function Start()\\n\\ttool.Equipped:Connect(Equipped)\\n\\ttool.Unequipped:Connect(Unequipped)\\nend\\n\\nStart()\\n  \\n And here is my tool’s  server  sided code: \\n  local tool = script.Parent\\nlocal handle = tool.Handle\\nlocal handleGrip = handle.PrimaryMotor\\nlocal event = tool:WaitForChild(\\"DrillRigEvent\\")\\n\\nlocal function EventCalled(player:Player,eventType:string)\\n\\tlocal character = player.Character\\n\\tlocal humanoid = character:FindFirstChild(\\"Humanoid\\")\\n\\tlocal humanoidRootPart = character:FindFirstChild(\\"Humanoid", "upvotes": 0, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 1, "created_at": "2026-01-01T07:58:47.157Z"}
784	devforum	4203823	How to detect if the mouse is clicking a part inside a worldmodel(on a viewportframe)	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4203823	Scripting	Camera:ViewportPointToRay() fails to return correct rays when used with a ViewportFrame because it calculates based on the main screen resolution rather than the UI element's AbsoluteSize, preventing accurate raycasting for parts inside a WorldModel.	Manually calculate the ray by normalizing the mouse coordinates relative to the ViewportFrame's AbsoluteSize (mapping to a -1 to 1 range) and using the Camera's FieldOfView and AspectRatio to derive the specific look direction.	t	intermediate	{ViewportFrame,WorldModel,Camera,ViewportPointToRay,Raycast,RaycastParams,UserInputService,AbsoluteSize,AbsolutePosition}	{}	t	An automated agent can provide a boilerplate function that performs the 3D math required to generate a ray for a ViewportFrame, taking into account FOV and AspectRatio, which is a common recurring obstacle in Roblox UI development.	116	6	11	2026-01-01 04:02:06.084	2026-01-08 17:19:50.296916	{"views": 116, "content": " I’m trying to detect mouse clicks on Parts/Models inside a WorldModel that’s rendered in a fullscreen ViewportFrame. The goal is simply to know which model the player clicked. \\n The problem is that the click  is not being detected at all  on the objects inside the WorldModel. Since this is a ViewportFrame,  Mouse.Target  doesn’t work, and the raycast I’m using isn’t hitting anything. \\n This is the script I tried: \\n  local function GetClickedModel(part)\\n\\twhile part and not part:IsA(\\"Model\\") do\\n\\t\\tpart = part.Parent\\n\\tend\\n\\treturn part\\nend\\n\\nlocal function DetectCardClick(input)\\n\\tif input.UserInputType ~= Enum.UserInputType.MouseButton1 then return end\\n\\n\\tlocal mousePos = UserInputService:GetMouseLocation()\\n\\tlocal framePos = ViewPortFrame.AbsolutePosition\\n\\tlocal frameSize = ViewPortFrame.AbsoluteSize\\n\\n\\tlocal relX = mousePos.X - framePos.X\\n\\tlocal relY = mousePos.Y - framePos.Y\\n\\n\\tif relX &lt; 0 or relY &lt; 0 or relX &gt; frameSize.X or relY &gt; frameSize.Y then\\n\\t\\treturn\\n\\tend\\n\\n\\tlocal ray = ViewPortCam:ViewportPointToRay(relX, relY)\\n\\n\\tlocal params = RaycastParams.new()\\n\\tparams.FilterType = Enum.RaycastFilterType.Whitelist\\n\\tparams.FilterDescendantsInstances = { ViewPortFrame.WorldModel }\\n\\tparams.IgnoreWater = true\\n\\n\\tlocal result = workspace:Raycast(\\n\\t\\tray.Origin,\\n\\t\\tray.Direction * 1000,\\n\\t\\tparams\\n\\t)\\n\\n\\tif result then\\n\\t\\tlocal model = GetClickedModel(result.Instance)\\n\\t\\tif model then\\n\\t\\t\\tprint(\\"Model clicked:\\", model.Name)\\n\\t\\tend\\n\\tend\\nend\\n  \\n The ViewportFrame is fullscreen, has its own Camera, and all clickable objects are inside a WorldModel. \\n   \\n     ", "upvotes": 6, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 11, "created_at": "2026-01-01T04:02:06.084Z"}
