833	devforum	4181825	How can I tell what a Roblox method returns and what arguments its events pass to connected functions?	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4181825	Scripting	Understanding how arguments are passed from Roblox signals to connected functions and how to identify these parameters when documentation is unclear.	Arguments are automatically passed by the signal (RBXScriptSignal) to the connected function as parameters. While some documentation headers may omit them, they can be identified via Studio's autocomplete, code samples in the documentation, or by the specific context of the event (e.g., .Touched passes the hitting Part).	t	beginner	{CollectionService:GetInstanceAddedSignal,RBXScriptSignal:Connect,BasePart.Touched,Players.PlayerAdded}	{}	t	A coding agent or IDE tool can use the Roblox API dump to automatically provide the signature and type-hinting for callback functions passed to :Connect.	101	5	3	2025-12-25 04:56:41.149	2026-01-08 17:20:56.611493	{"views": 101, "content": " The code below is an already working code I got from a tutorial I was watching on CollectionService and I couldn’t figure out how it worked. \\n  CollectionService:GetInstanceAddedSignal('KillBrick'):Connect(function(instance)\\n\\tinstance.Touched:Connect(function(hit)\\n\\t\\tif hit.Parent:FindFirstChild('HumanoidRootPart') and hit.Parent.Humanoid.Health &gt; 0 then\\n\\t\\t\\thit.Parent.Humanoid.Health = 0\\n\\t\\tend\\n\\tend)\\nend)\\n  \\n These are the two questions I have: \\n  1.  How does this script know what ‘instance’ is even I never defined it anywhere.  \\n The best explanation I could find for this is that the method ‘GetInstanceAddedSignal’ sort of passes an instance argument to the function it is connected to, but this doesn’t seem to be mentioned in the CollectionService documentations:  https://create.roblox.com/docs/reference/engine/classes/CollectionService#GetInstanceAddedSignal  \\n  2. If the explanation that the method passes arguments to its connected function is true, then how can I know what kind of argument it is passing or if it even passes an argument at all in the future?  ", "upvotes": 5, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 3, "created_at": "2025-12-25T04:56:41.149Z"}
