886	devforum	4188928	Some questions about threads, task.spawn and coroutines	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4188928	Scripting	Conceptual confusion regarding the distinction between Luau threads (coroutines), system threads, and how the Task Scheduler manages event-based execution vs. loops.	A thread in Luau is an execution context (coroutine), not a hardware thread. Luau is single-threaded and utilizes cooperative multitasking, meaning only one thread runs at a time and must yield to allow others to process. The Task Scheduler handles all Luau execution, including events like Touched, by resuming them at specific points in the engine's frame cycle.	t	intermediate	{task.spawn,task.wait,coroutine,debug.profilebegin,debug.profileend,Touched}	{}	f	A coding agent could provide documentation or diagrams illustrating the Roblox Task Scheduler lifecycle and the Luau VM's single-threaded execution model.	248	11	29	2025-12-27 12:29:29.328	2026-01-08 17:22:52.005785	{"views": 248, "content": " Just tell me if everything i’m saying is on the right lines or is correct and anything that’s incorrect you can correct me on. \\n Okay so i’ve looked far and wide. The definition of a thread in context to luau is quite mixed. But from all my research and my own thoughts I’ve gathered the idea that a thread is basically just the code that we execute in scripts right? A set of instructions essentially? \\n So like for example in this code there is one main thread (basically all of the code) and then new threads are created each time the touched event is fired right? \\n  -- Everything else from the start to the end is the \\"main thread\\"\\nlocal ReplicatedStorage = game:GetService(\\"ReplicatedStorage\\")\\n\\nTouched:Connect(function(hit)\\n-- New thread created and ran here\\nend)\\n\\nwhile true do\\ntask.wait()\\nend\\n  \\n Then, task.spawn and coroutines don’t actually create new threads. They create new virtual/emulated threads, so bsaically not real ones right? Then why is it that in the microprofiler when I use debug.profilebegin/end and I seperate code with task.spawn/coroutines from other code in the script, I see the labelled tasks and in the microprofiler it shows me how the code ran in task.spawn is actually ran AFTER the code in the main thread (the main code of the script). \\n Another thing, the labels that are shown in the microprofiler. (The coloured coded ones not the labels on the left hand side like main and RBX worker) Are they represented as tasks or threads (a set of code, because threads are basically that right? a set of code). \\n And actually, the labelled threads like RBX worker and main. They are like main main threads right? And my code is like a mini thread  part of those main main threads?? Idk I word it all kinda weirdly but I hope u guys get it. \\n Also, the task scheduler schedules the tasks that are done every frame. That means only code that runs very frequently eg while loops and runservice events are done in the task scheduler right? So if I had part.Touched:Conne", "upvotes": 11, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 29, "created_at": "2025-12-27T12:29:29.328Z"}
887	devforum	4195439	Problem with grid snapping and CFrame.lookAt()	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4195439	Scripting	Discrepancy between model pivot position and internal part positions when using CFrame.lookAt with grid-snapped coordinates and a custom up-vector.	\N	f	intermediate	{CFrame.lookAt,Vector3.new,math.floor,PVInstance:PivotTo,task.wait}	{}	t	An agent could analyze the CFrame.lookAt up-vector (Vector3.new(0, 0, 1)) which might cause gimbal lock or orientation issues when the look-vector aligns with the Z-axis, and suggest a distance check to prevent CFrame errors when start and end positions are identical due to snapping.	53	8	5	2025-12-29 14:29:57.9	2026-01-08 17:22:53.420559	{"views": 53, "content": " Hey there!   \\n I’m making a road-building system, but I’ve run into an issue with grid snapping and CFrame.lookAt(). Firstly, I’d like to place the start segment of the road, then rotate it towards the end segment. The end segment should also rotate towards the start. This is my code so far: \\n  local xGrid = 4\\n\\nlocal function gridSnap(pos)\\n\\treturn Vector3.new(\\n\\t\\tmath.floor(pos.X / xGrid + 0.5) * xGrid,\\n\\t\\tpos.Y,\\n\\t\\tmath.floor(pos.Z / xGrid + 0.5) * xGrid\\n\\t)\\nend\\n\\n-- (getting the start position...)\\n\\nwhile task.wait() do\\n\\tlocal ray = mouseRay()\\n\\n\\tif ray then\\n\\t\\tlocal endPos = gridSnap(ray.Position)\\n\\t\\troadEnd.Parent = game.Workspace\\n\\n\\t\\troadEnd:PivotTo(CFrame.lookAt(endPos, startPos, Vector3.new(0, 0, 1)))\\n\\n\\t\\troadStart:PivotTo(CFrame.lookAt(startPos, endPos, Vector3.new(0, 0, 1)))\\n\\tend\\nend\\n  \\n If the snapping is enabled for the start segment and disabled for the end segment, the system seems to work: \\n  \\n     \\n If the snapping is enabled for both the start and end segments, this happens: \\n  \\n     \\n The printed position of the actual model seems to be correct, though when I click on the parts within the model, the position is completely off: \\n         image  657×160 3.41 KB         \\n If anybody has ideas on why this is happening, please let me know! Thank you! ", "upvotes": 8, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 5, "created_at": "2025-12-29T14:29:57.900Z"}
