l\\n    end\\n\\n    if camera then\\n        if not baseCFrameValue or baseCFrameValue.Parent ~= camera then\\n            baseCFrameValue = Instance.new(\\"CFrameValue\\")\\n            baseCFrameValue.Name = \\"UnshakenCFrame\\"\\n            baseCFrameValue.Archivable = false\\n            baseCFrameValue.Value = camera.CFrame\\n            baseCFrameValue.Parent = camera\\n        end\\n\\n        if not aiming() and math.abs(camera.FieldOfView - BASE_FOV) &gt; 0.05 then\\n            camera.FieldOfView = BASE_FOV\\n        end\\n    end\\nend\\n\\nlocal lastBaseCF = CFrame.new()\\n\\nlocal strafingSignal = humanoid:FindFirstChild(\\"Strafing\\")\\nif strafingSignal then\\n    strafingSignal.Changed:Connect(function(val)\\n        strafing = val\\n    end)\\nend\\n\\nhumanoid.Running:Connect(function(speed)\\n    running = speed ", "upvotes": 3, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 11, "created_at": "2025-12-27T15:18:20.492Z"}
895	devforum	4188279	Detecting if character is behind target when target is facing straight up/down results in wrong result	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4188279	Scripting	Backstab detection logic using Dot product and XZ-plane projection fails when the target character is facing vertically (pointing straight up or down), causing the LookVector's X and Z components to flip or become near-zero.	\N	f	intermediate	{Vector3,CFrame,LookVector,Dot}	{}	t	A coding agent could suggest using the CFrame's UpVector as an alternative reference when the LookVector is parallel to the Y-axis, or recommend calculating the angle based on the target's Top surface/root orientation rather than a raw projected LookVector.	124	4	6	2025-12-27 06:48:20.241	2026-01-08 17:23:09.325794	{"views": 124, "content": " In one of my projects, you are able to be ragdolled through attacks and such,  which can result in the character facing straight upwards or straight downwards.  \\n The method I use to detect if the character is backstabbing a target is: \\n  local X_Z = Vector3.new(1, 0, 1)\\nlocal TargetLook = TargetCFrame.LookVector * X_Z\\nlocal RelativeDirection = TargetCFrame.Position - SourceCFrame.Position\\nif RelativeDirection.Unit:Dot((TargetLook).Unit) &gt;= 0.5 then\\n--is behind, backstab/ignore blocking\\n  \\n As the character’s lookvector faces straight up/down, the X and Z vectors of the LookVector changes due to the angle of the character being flipped. \\n I believe this is due to a phenomenon called gimbal locking. How can I combat this? \\n          {E42CEA7F-74E6-41BC-A0E5-45B18E69BCE9}  698×458 20.4 KB         \\n          {9C43296F-03C0-4A09-865B-C8F497A7B00B}  634×372 40.7 KB         ", "upvotes": 4, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 6, "created_at": "2025-12-27T06:48:20.241Z"}
