sses.Name = \\"losses\\"\\n\\tlosses.Parent = leaderstats\\n\\n\\tlocal ties = Instance.new(\\"NumberValue\\")\\n\\tties.Name = \\"ties\\"\\n\\tties.Parent = leaderstats\\n\\n\\t\\n\\tlocal data\\n\\tlocal success, err = pcall(function()\\n\\t\\tdata = dataStore:GetAsync(player.UserId)\\n\\tend)\\n\\n\\tif success and data then\\n\\n\\t\\twins.Value = data[1]\\n\\t\\tties.Value = data[2]\\n\\t\\tlosses.Value = data[3]\\n\\t\\tstreak.Value = data[4]\\n\\n\\telse\\n\\t\\tprint(\\"The player has no data!\\")\\n\\tend\\n\\nend)\\ngame.Players.PlayerRemoving:Connect(function(player)\\n\\tsaveData(player)\\nend)\\n\\ngame:BindToClose(function()\\n\\tfor _, player in pairs(game.Players:GetPlayers()) do\\n\\t\\tsaveData(player)\\n\\tend\\nend)\\n  ", "upvotes": 0, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 4, "created_at": "2025-12-28T02:18:11.494Z"}
931	devforum	4188036	Using PivotTo() to move the model before spawning it causes the weld positions to become incorrect	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4188036	Physics	Legacy Weld objects break or cause misaligned parts when moving models to distant coordinates due to floating-point precision issues in C0/C1 calculations.	Replace legacy Weld objects with WeldConstraint, which handles relative offsets automatically and is more robust during teleportation or initial placement.	t	intermediate	{PivotTo,MoveTo,Weld,WeldConstraint,CFrame,inverse,Clone}	{}	t	An automated script can iterate through existing Welds or part-joining scripts and replace legacy Weld logic with WeldConstraint assignments, removing the need for manual C0 and C1 CFrame inversion math.	77	3	3	2025-12-27 04:49:35.491	2026-01-08 17:24:29.385508	{"views": 77, "content": "          RobloxScreenShot20251227_134102550  1601×681 112 KB         \\nThis is the locomotive in proper working order. \\n          RobloxScreenShot20251227_134027998  1601×681 125 KB         \\nUsing PivotTo() to spawn it at a distant location causes the weld to break. \\n Is there a way to fix this? \\nOr is it due to a floating-point error and therefore unfixable? \\n  script.Parent.MouseClick:Connect(function()\\n\\tlocal clone = workspace.Loco:Clone()\\n\\tclone:MoveTo(script.Parent.Parent.Parent.SpawnBase.CFrame)\\n\\tclone.Parent = workspace\\nend)\\n  \\n  local PrimaryPart = script.Parent.PrimaryPart\\nlocal Parts = script.Parent:GetChildren()\\n\\nfor i = 1, #Parts do\\n\\tif Parts[i]:IsA(\\"BasePart\\") then\\n\\t\\tlocal weld = Instance.new(\\"Weld\\")\\n\\t\\tweld.Part0 = PrimaryPart\\n\\t\\tweld.Part1 = Parts[i]\\n\\t\\tweld.C0 = PrimaryPart.CFrame:inverse()\\n\\t\\tweld.C1 = Parts[i].CFrame:inverse()\\n\\t\\tweld.Parent = PrimaryPart\\n\\tend\\nend\\n  ", "upvotes": 3, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 3, "created_at": "2025-12-27T04:49:35.491Z"}
