964	devforum	4186060	Is OOP in Luau Actually a Bad Practice?	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4186060	Scripting	Performance overhead and architectural complexity of metatable-based Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) in Luau.	Metatable lookups in Luau create significant overhead compared to standard table lookups. While OOP offers organization, alternatives like Entity Component Systems (ECS) or simpler procedural patterns are often more performant and less prone to overengineering in Luau.	t	intermediate	{setmetatable,getmetatable,luaH_get}	{}	f	A coding agent could help by refactoring deep OOP class hierarchies into flatter structures, implementing ECS boilerplate, or using Luau's 'export type' for better type checking without the overhead of metatables.	842	68	46	2025-12-26 16:10:05.07	2026-01-08 17:25:43.801512	{"views": 842, "content": " I’ve been working with Lua for a while now, and I keep running into this debate:  Is using OOP in Lua considered bad practice?  \\n I see a lot of conflicting opinions in the community, and I’m trying to figure out the right approach for my projects. \\n  Lua doesn’t have native OOP support.  Unlike languages with built-in classes, we have to implement OOP using metatables and table manipulation. This feels like we’re forcing a paradigm onto a language that wasn’t designed for it. Some specific issues I’m worried about: \\n \\n  Performance : Does the metatable lookup chain create significant overhead? \\n  Memory usage : Am I wasting memory by giving each instance metatable references? \\n  Complexity : Am I overengineering solutions by building class systems when simpler approaches exist? \\n \\n   But I Also See Benefits \\n On the other hand, for larger projects, OOP seems to provide: \\n \\n Better organization and encapsulation \\n Clear interfaces and responsibilities \\n Code reuse through inheritance or composition \\n Natural modeling of game entities (players, enemies, items, etc.) \\n \\n Many problems just  feel  object-oriented. Game entities, UI components, state machines—these seem to map naturally to OOP patterns. \\n   My Questions \\n \\n  Is OOP in Lua generally considered bad practice , or is it just a matter of when and how you use it? \\n  What are the actual performance implications?  Are we talking negligible overhead or something that matters in production? \\n  When should I use OOP vs other paradigms in Lua?  Are there clear guidelines or is it purely subjective? \\n ", "upvotes": 68, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 46, "created_at": "2025-12-26T16:10:05.070Z"}
