1001	devforum	4181532	Client-side tweens playing choppy, segmented when the client did not call the remote event	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4181532	Scripting	Client-side tweens appear choppy or segmented in Roblox Studio Local Server testing when the specific client window is not focused.	This is expected behavior in Roblox Studio. Studio automatically throttles the frame rate and performance of non-focused windows to save system resources. The code works correctly in a live environment or when the window is focused.	t	beginner	{TweenService,RemoteEvent,UserInputService,RunService}	{}	f	An AI agent can identify that visual choppiness during multi-client Studio testing is often a result of engine-level performance throttling rather than logic errors, and suggest checking the 'Background Frame Rate' settings or testing in a live game.	113	3	6	2025-12-25 01:56:30.295	2026-01-08 17:27:01.283467	{"views": 113, "content": " I want to have both client-side tweens that are called by a server event move an attachment smoothly. When one client sends an input to call a remote the server fires an event on all clients that plays the tween on an attachment. The client that sent the remote event has a normal tween, while the other’s segmented and stays in one spot before teleporting to the next, instead of a smooth transition. This is odd because both the attachment and tween are handled by the client. \\n I recreated the problem in an example game here: \\n tweenExample.rbxl  (76.0 KB) \\n Here is a video demonstrating the problem, a part is being repeatedly created on the tweened attachment to demonstrate: \\n  \\n     \\n local script \\n  local uis = game:GetService(\\"UserInputService\\")\\nlocal player = game.Players.LocalPlayer\\nlocal char = player.Character or player.CharacterAdded:Wait()\\nlocal hum = char:WaitForChild(\\"Humanoid\\")\\nlocal camera = workspace.CurrentCamera\\nlocal tweenService = game:GetService(\\"TweenService\\")\\nlocal runService = game:GetService(\\"RunService\\")\\nlocal playerGui = player:WaitForChild(\\"PlayerGui\\")\\n\\nuis.InputBegan:Connect(function(input, gameprocessed)\\n\\tif gameprocessed then return end\\n\\tif input.KeyCode == Enum.KeyCode.E then\\n\\t\\tgame.ReplicatedStorage.RemoteEvent:FireServer()\\n\\tend\\nend)\\n\\ngame.ReplicatedStorage.RemoteEvent.OnClientEvent:Connect(function()\\n\\tlocal attachment0 = Instance.new(\\"Attachment\\")\\n\\tlocal attachment1 = Instance.new(\\"Attachment\\")\\n\\tlocal startPoint = player.Character[\\"Right Arm\\"].Position - player.Character[\\"Right Arm\\"].CFrame.UpVector\\n\\tlocal endPoint = player.Character.HumanoidRootPart.Position + player.Character.HumanoidRootPart.CFrame.LookVector*30\\n\\tattachment0.Parent = player.Character[\\"Right Arm\\"]\\n\\tattachment0.WorldPosition =  startPoint\\n\\tattachment1.Position = startPoint\\n\\tattachment0.Orientation = Vector3.new(0, 0, 90)\\n\\tattachment1.Orientation = Vector3.new(0, 0, 90)\\n\\tattachment1.Parent = workspace\\n\\tlocal beam = Instance.new(\\"Beam\\")\\n\\tbeam.Texture = \\"rbxassetid://12", "upvotes": 3, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 6, "created_at": "2025-12-25T01:56:30.295Z"}
1002	devforum	4176039	How would you let Cmdr commands bypass your anticheat system?	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4176039	Scripting	Exempting Cmdr command-driven movements from a custom teleport anti-cheat system without manually editing every command's logic module.	Use Cmdr Hooks to set a temporary flag on the player character when a command is executed. Additionally, use Registry:RegisterCommandsIn to manage custom command logic and transition the anti-cheat from kicking to 'rubberbanding' (teleporting back) to handle false positives from lag or commands.	t	intermediate	{Cmdr,Registry:RegisterCommandsIn}	{}	t	Create a Cmdr 'BeforeRun' hook to set a temporary attribute on the player (e.g., 'CmdrBypassing') and an 'AfterRun' hook to remove it. Update the anti-cheat script to check for this attribute before flagging movement.	210	2	12	2025-12-23 09:43:02.454	2026-01-08 17:27:04.381975	{"views": 210, "content": " I’m using  Cmdr by evaera  and I have a custom anticheat system. One anticheat check I have is teleport where it checks if the player’s new position is 25 studs or more than the last position then the anticheat kicks them from the game. \\n I also have a teleport/bring command in Cmdr which teleports a player to another player. \\n How would be able to let all Cmdr commands and players affected by the command bypass the anticheat without modifying all command logic modules? \\n \\n \\nIf needed– Cmdr Commands setup: \\n ServerScriptService \\n → CmdrServer (normal script) \\n → -&gt; Commands (folder) \\n → -&gt; → e.g. Modules for one server command: teleport and teleportServer (teleportServer is logic) \\n → -&gt; Hooks (folder) \\n → -&gt; Types (folder) \\n ", "upvotes": 2, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 12, "created_at": "2025-12-23T09:43:02.454Z"}
1003	devforum	4181982	How to convert direction to angle?	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4181982	Scripting	How to convert a 3D direction vector to a rotation or Euler angles to align one part's orientation with another.	Use CFrame.lookAt(Position, LookVector) to orient a part towards a direction vector. For manual mathematical calculation, trigonometric functions like math.atan2 (for yaw) and math.asin (for pitch) can be used to derive angles from vector components.	t	intermediate	{CFrame.lookAt,CFrame.new,CFrame.lookVector}	{}	t	An AI agent can provide boilerplate code for vector-to-angle conversion using math.atan2 or generate CFrame construction logic using the lookAt method.	151	3	8	2025-12-25 06:25:48.205	2026-01-08 17:27:04.543324	{"views": 151, "content": " does anyone know how to convert a 3d direction to an angle that my part would rotate to? \\n i am not referring to UI or other related graphical user interface \\n basically what i want to do is make my part have the same orientation as the other part by getting the other part’s direction then convert it to an angle so the parts would have the same orientation \\n ask some questions if your confused ", "upvotes": 3, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 8, "created_at": "2025-12-25T06:25:48.205Z"}
1015	devforum	4180254	I need help making a sounds module	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4180254	Networking	Creating an optimized sound replication module to sync audio playback from one client to all other clients via a server relay.	Use a RemoteEvent to send sound data from the initiating client to the server, which then uses :FireAllClients() to signal all other clients to play the sound locally.	t	beginner	{RemoteEvent,FireServer,FireAllClients}	{}	t	A coding agent can generate a standard client-server relay boilerplate that includes a RemoteEvent in ReplicatedStorage, a ServerScriptService relay script, and a LocalScript listener to handle Sound instance creation and playback.	81	4	7	2025-12-24 16:32:46.226	2026-01-08 17:27:30.220027	{"views": 81, "content": " How can I make an optimized sounds replication module with no prior knowledge of buffers or how caching works? \\n I want to be able to replicate a sound request from a client to all other clients. I was hoping if anyone could provide any sort of guidance ", "upvotes": 4, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 7, "created_at": "2025-12-24T16:32:46.226Z"}
1004	devforum	4171125	Frame dependency	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4171125	Scripting	Frame-dependent movement speed and inconsistent inertia due to improper use of delta time in Lerp functions and velocity calculations within RenderStepped.	Apply frame-rate independent interpolation using the formula '1 - (decay_rate ^ delta)' for the lerp alpha, or normalize velocity magnitudes by multiplying by 'delta * target_fps' (e.g., delta * 60).	t	intermediate	{RunService.RenderStepped,UserInputService,HumanoidRootPart.AssemblyLinearVelocity,Vector3:Lerp,CFrame.LookVector,CFrame.RightVector}	{}	t	An agent can scan loops tied to RunService events (Heartbeat/RenderStepped) for Vector3 or CFrame Lerp calls that use a constant alpha or a simple 'delta * constant' multiplication, and suggest replacing them with mathematically accurate exponential decay formulas for frame independence.	201	11	20	2025-12-21 20:41:45.605	2026-01-08 17:27:09.542714	{"views": 201, "content": " So, I’ve tried making a simple movement script for simulating inertia and/or realistic movement. The issue I have is that the speed is frame-dependent. (for some fricking reason). \\n Here’s the code: \\n  local statsF = game.Players.LocalPlayer:WaitForChild(\\"Stats\\")\\nlocal walkSpeed = statsF:WaitForChild(\\"WalkSpeed\\").Value\\nlocal runSpeed = statsF:WaitForChild(\\"RunSpeed\\").Value\\n\\nlocal char = script.Parent\\nlocal hum = char:WaitForChild(\\"Humanoid\\")\\nlocal rootPart = char:WaitForChild(\\"HumanoidRootPart\\")\\n\\nlocal userInputService = game:GetService(\\"UserInputService\\")\\nlocal runService = game:GetService(\\"RunService\\")\\n\\nlocal desiredSpeed = Vector3.zero\\nlocal speed = Vector3.zero\\n\\nlocal forward\\nlocal backward\\nlocal left\\nlocal right\\n\\nlocal forwardVelocity = Vector3.zero\\nlocal sidewaysVelocity = Vector3.zero\\n\\nlocal multiplyer = 1.1\\n\\nuserInputService.InputBegan:Connect(function(input, gameProc)\\n\\tif not gameProc then\\n\\t\\tif input.UserInputType == Enum.UserInputType.Keyboard then\\n\\t\\t\\tif input.KeyCode == Enum.KeyCode.W then\\n\\t\\t\\t\\tforward = true\\n\\t\\t\\telseif input.KeyCode == Enum.KeyCode.S then\\n\\t\\t\\t\\tbackward = true\\n\\t\\t\\telseif input.KeyCode == Enum.KeyCode.D then\\n\\t\\t\\t\\tright = true\\n\\t\\t\\telseif input.KeyCode == Enum.KeyCode.A then\\n\\t\\t\\t\\tleft = true\\n\\t\\t\\tend\\n\\t\\tend\\n\\tend\\nend)\\n\\nuserInputService.InputEnded:Connect(function(input, gameProc)\\n\\tif not gameProc then\\n\\t\\tif input.UserInputType == Enum.UserInputType.Keyboard then\\n\\t\\t\\tif input.KeyCode == Enum.KeyCode.W then\\n\\t\\t\\t\\tforward = false\\n\\t\\t\\telseif input.KeyCode == Enum.KeyCode.S then\\n\\t\\t\\t\\tbackward = false\\n\\t\\t\\telseif input.KeyCode == Enum.KeyCode.D then\\n\\t\\t\\t\\tright = false\\n\\t\\t\\telseif input.KeyCode == Enum.KeyCode.A then\\n\\t\\t\\t\\tleft = false\\n\\t\\t\\tend\\n\\t\\tend\\n\\tend\\nend)\\n\\nrunService.RenderStepped:Connect(function(delta)\\n\\tif forward then\\n\\t\\tforwardVelocity = rootPart.CFrame.LookVector * walkSpeed * multiplyer\\n\\tend\\n\\tif backward then\\n\\t\\tforwardVelocity = rootPart.CFrame.LookVector * -walkSpeed * multiplyer\\n\\tend\\n\\tif left then\\n\\t\\tsidewaysVelocity = rootPart.CFrame.RightVector * -walkSpeed * ", "upvotes": 11, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 20, "created_at": "2025-12-21T20:41:45.605Z"}
1005	devforum	4181972	Unknown type 'setmetatable' type error. Why?	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4181972	Scripting	The generic 'setmetatable' type syntax is being flagged as an 'unknown type' error in Luau strict mode.	The 'setmetatable<T, U>' type syntax is only supported when the 'New Luau Type Solver' is enabled. Ensure 'New Luau Type Solver' is enabled in Studio Beta Features and check that 'Workspace.UseNewLuauTypeSolver' is not disabled in Team Create settings.	t	intermediate	{setmetatable}	{"Unknown type 'setmetatable'"}	t	A coding agent could verify if the project settings or environment support the New Luau Type Solver before suggesting type definitions that use generic setmetatable syntax.	61	1	4	2025-12-25 06:23:01.663	2026-01-08 17:27:09.586158	{"views": 61, "content": "  --!strict\\n\\ntype Map = {\\n\\tName : string;\\n\\tIcon : string;\\n}\\ntype MapSlot = {\\n\\t__index : MapSlot;\\n\\tnew : (Map) -&gt; setmetatable&lt;{}, {__index : typeof(MapSlot)}&gt;;\\n}\\n\\nlocal mapSlot = {} :: MapSlot\\nmapSlot.__index = mapSlot\\n\\nfunction mapSlot.new(map : Map)\\n\\treturn setmetatable({}, mapSlot)\\nend\\n\\n  \\n Warning occurs on line 9: \\n  \\nWhat am I doing wrong? ", "upvotes": 1, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 4, "created_at": "2025-12-25T06:23:01.663Z"}
1006	devforum	4175062	Enemy will chase a random player, but not the closest	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4175062	Scripting	The NPC targets the last player in the player list instead of the closest one because the direction vector variable is overwritten in every loop iteration, but used outside the loop.	Store the direction vector inside the 'if' statement that checks for the shortest distance, ensuring that the vector corresponds to the identified 'Target1' rather than the final player in the GetPlayers() table.	t	beginner	{game.Players:GetPlayers,Vector3.new,CFrame.lookAt,Humanoid.TakeDamage,Humanoid.RootPart}	{}	t	An automated script analysis tool could detect that the variable 'CalculatedDistance' is assigned inside a loop but used outside of it, with its value being overwritten in every iteration regardless of the 'if' condition that selects the target.	112	6	9	2025-12-23 00:49:25.094	2026-01-08 17:27:10.410544	{"views": 112, "content": " I’m trying to recreate a game named Rooms: Low Detailed (it has since been deleted), but the entity refuses to attack me, and only attacks my friend. How can I fix this? \\n              \\n \\nCode: \\n  local AimMultiplier = Vector3.new(0.5, 0, 0.5)\\nwhile wait() do\\n\\tlocal Target1 = nil\\n\\tlocal CalculatedDistance = Vector3.new()\\n\\tlocal Distance1 = math.huge\\n\\tfor _, Player in pairs(game.Players:GetPlayers()) do\\n\\t\\tlocal Target2 = Player.Character or Player.CharacterAdded:Wait()\\n\\t\\tlocal Humanoid = Target2:FindFirstChildOfClass(\\"Humanoid\\")\\n\\t\\tlocal RootPart = Humanoid.RootPart\\n\\t\\tlocal Distance2 = RootPart.Position\\n\\t\\tCalculatedDistance = Distance2 - script.Parent.Position\\n\\t\\tlocal CMag = CalculatedDistance.Magnitude\\n\\t\\tif CMag &lt; Distance1 and not Target2:FindFirstChild(\\"Hidden\\") then\\n\\t\\t\\tDistance1 = CMag\\n\\t\\t\\tTarget1 = Target2\\n\\t\\tend\\n\\tend\\n\\tif Target1 and Distance1 &lt; 50 and Target1:FindFirstChildOfClass(\\"Humanoid\\").Health &gt; 0 then\\n\\t\\tscript.Parent.CFrame += CFrame.lookAt(script.Parent.Position, script.Parent.Position + CalculatedDistance).LookVector * AimMultiplier\\n\\t\\tif Distance1 &lt; 10 then\\n\\t\\t\\tTarget1:FindFirstChildOfClass(\\"Humanoid\\"):TakeDamage(1)\\n\\t\\tend\\n\\telse\\n\\t\\tscript.Parent.CFrame -= Vector3.new(0, 0, 0.5)\\n\\tend\\n\\tif script.Parent.Position.Z &lt; -100 then\\n\\t\\tscript.Parent:Destroy()\\n\\tend\\nend\\n  ", "upvotes": 6, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 9, "created_at": "2025-12-23T00:49:25.094Z"}
1007	devforum	3314524	Normal Tables vs Buffers, are buffers really that cost effective?	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/3314524	Networking	Evaluating the network efficiency and data size benefits of using the buffer type versus standard Lua tables for RemoteEvent data transmission.	Buffers are significantly more efficient for large datasets or strict limits (like the 900-byte UnreliableRemoteEvent cap) because they allow for precise bit-level packing (e.g., using 2 bytes for a short vs 8 bytes for a standard Lua number). For small, simple tables, the size difference is often negligible, and the convenience of tables may outweigh the minor memory optimization.	t	intermediate	{RemoteEvent,UnreliableRemoteEvent,buffer}	{}	t	A coding agent could provide templates or helper functions to automatically pack and unpack structured data into buffers to minimize boilerplate code while maintaining network efficiency.	1710	2	5	2024-12-22 09:59:37.884	2026-01-08 17:27:14.925916	{"views": 1710, "content": " Hello! \\n I’ve probably seen many developers saying that using buffer will help you lower data size especially when using remote event to transfer data. \\n But are they really? \\n As a far I know buffers are a very primitive type of data storage, down to the individual bits of data. For which they say that if used properly they can reduce data passing significantly. But when using a very simple set of data (eg just a array of integers) is compressing still useful? \\n Just passing a simple set of data, \\n  -- a remote event (assume)\\nlocal Event \\n-- normal table with integers\\nlocal tab = {0,1,20,7}\\n\\n-- a buffer with the same integers as 8-bit unsigned shorts (assume)\\nlocal buf\\n\\n-- Sending the data\\nEvent:FireServer(tab)\\nEvent:FireServer(bug)\\n  \\n I assume in this case Roblox may compress the table to pass. But is it better to use buffers? ", "upvotes": 2, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 5, "created_at": "2024-12-22T09:59:37.884Z"}
1016	devforum	4179880	Help with baldi npc	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4179880	Scripting	Incorrect implementation of PathfindingService where waypoints are generated but not iterated over, and logic creates redundant infinite loops for every player.	Iterate through the waypoints array returned by PathfindingService and use MoveTo for each point. Additionally, refactor the code to find the nearest player in a single loop rather than spawning nested infinite loops for every player entry.	t	beginner	{PathfindingService,Humanoid,HumanoidRootPart,CreatePath,GetWaypoints,MoveTo}	{}	t	A coding agent could provide a template for a 'chase' script that includes ComputeAsync, waypoints iteration, and a magnitude check to target the closest player.	138	1	8	2025-12-24 14:02:08.073	2026-01-08 17:27:32.281518	{"views": 138, "content": " i am trying to do an baldi npc with pathfinding, but i cant make he chase the player, the code: \\"local pathfindingService = game:GetService(“PathfindingService”) \\nlocal npc = script.Parent \\nlocal npc_humanoid = npc.Humanoid \\nlocal npc_hrp = npc.HumanoidRootPart \\nlocal players = game:GetService(“Players”) \\nlocal path = pathfindingService:CreatePath({ \\nAgentCanClimb = false, \\nAgentCanJump = false, \\nAgentRadius = 0.7 \\n}) \\n local waypoints = path:GetWaypoints() \\nlocal wait_to_slap = npc:WaitForChild(“Configuration”).SlapIntervalValue.Value \\n npc_hrp.Touched:Connect(function(hit) \\nif hit.Parent:FindFirstChild(“Humanoid”) then \\nhit:BreakJoints() \\nend \\nend) \\n for i, player in pairs(players:GetPlayers()) do \\nif player then \\nlocal char = player.Character \\nlocal hrp = char:FindFirstChild(“HumanoidRootPart”) \\nwhile true do \\nwait(wait_to_slap) \\nnpc_humanoid:MoveTo(hrp.Position) \\nnpc_humanoid.MoveToFinished:Wait() \\nend \\nend \\nend \\" also if its weird its because i dont know to put code in a correct way on the forum, and i dont know how to use pathfinding proprerly ", "upvotes": 1, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 8, "created_at": "2025-12-24T14:02:08.073Z"}
1008	devforum	4181458	Scaling multiple parts in a Build Game causes it to drift off	https://devforum.roblox.com/t/4181458	Scripting	Scaling multiple parts with different rotations in a build system results in parts scaling along their individual local axes rather than a unified global/world axis, and an initial issue of parts drifting when scaled together.	\N	f	intermediate	{UserInputService,Camera,ViewportPointToRay,Vector3,CFrame}	{}	t	An automated agent could provide a CFrame transformation logic that converts a world-space drag vector into the local coordinate space of each selected object to calculate the correct size and position offsets.	67	1	4	2025-12-25 00:59:32.489	2026-01-08 17:27:16.178717	{"views": 67, "content": " I am trying to make a build system for my game where the players can move parts, scale parts, and rotate parts on their plot but there’s an issue. When the player scales a single part it works fine, but it slightly drifts off when they select more than 2 parts. I do not know how to solve this issue, and the way it scales is correct, not proportional scaling yet. \\n Here is what’s happening: \\n  \\n    \\nAnd here is the script:  \\n  elseif placedType == \\"Scale\\" then\\n\\t\\t\\tlocal currentPos = UserInputService:GetMouseLocation()\\n\\t\\t\\tlocal mouseRay = camera:ViewportPointToRay(currentPos.X, currentPos.Y)\\n\\t\\t\\tlocal currentT = getLineClosestParam(mouseRay.Origin, mouseRay.Direction, axisOrigin, dragDir)\\n\\t\\t\\tlocal delta = currentT - startDragT\\n\\t\\t\\tlocal moveDistance = tonumber(editGui.Frame.Building.Move.Text) or 1\\n\\t\\t\\tlocal snapSteps = math.round(delta / moveDistance)\\n\\t\\t\\tlocal snappedDelta = snapSteps * moveDistance\\n\\t\\t\\tlocal minClamp = math.max(moveDistance, 0.05)\\n\\t\\t\\tfor p, originalCF in pairs(initialPartCFrames) do\\n\\t\\t\\t\\tif p and p.Parent then\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tlocal origSize = initialPartSizes[p] or p.Size\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tlocal deltaApplied = snappedDelta\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tlocal newSize = origSize\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tif selectedAxis == \\"X\\" then\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tlocal desired = origSize.X + deltaApplied\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tlocal clamped = math.max(desired, minClamp)\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tdeltaApplied = clamped - origSize.X\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tnewSize = Vector3.new(clamped, origSize.Y, origSize.Z)\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\telseif selectedAxis == \\"Y\\" then\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tlocal desired = origSize.Y + deltaApplied\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tlocal clamped = math.max(desired, minClamp)\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tdeltaApplied = clamped - origSize.Y\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tnewSize = Vector3.new(origSize.X, clamped, origSize.Z)\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\telseif selectedAxis == \\"Z\\" then\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tlocal desired = origSize.Z + deltaApplied\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tlocal clamped = math.max(desired, minClamp)\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tdeltaApplied = clamped - origSize.Z\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tnewSize = Vector3.new(origSize.X, origSize.Y, clamped)\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tend\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tif deltaApplied ~= 0 then\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tp.Size = newSize\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tp.CFrame = originalCF + (dragDir * (deltaApplied * 0.5))\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t", "upvotes": 1, "category": "scripting-support", "comments": 4, "created_at": "2025-12-25T00:59:32.489Z"}
