 variable on the UI so let's actually do that and there you have it another thing I can put off my checklist let's see what else do I have in here here oh particle effects let's do that okay so real talk the Roblox particle system is really good like okay seriously look at this when you make a particle object you can modify things like color size transparency texture speed direction frequency how long it lives and more but then for some attributes you can open a graph to customize the value for any point during its life span and the changes apply in real time as you modify the graph and while I was writing this script I realized that you could even put a range of Randomness for any given point on the graph like yo that's so cool it gives you a lot of control while still being very easy to use okay uh I got a little carried away there but point is I added some particle effects when you touch a sphere awesome and finally I also put a glowing orb in the spot where the Spheres Spawn from and yeah that's about it for day five hey guys today we're going to be doing a Roblox game play oh okay day six let's speed things up the first thing I did was adding a little popup above your head when you grab a sphere and to achieve that I decided to use something called billboard GUI which basically allows you to have a UI element somewhere in 3D space about an hour later I got it working you know no big deal I was starting to get used to Roblox Studio following that I decided to split the money value into two things a score value that tracks how many points you have in the current game and a money value that tracks how many points you have in total because of that I had to rework most of the leaderboard and UI code which wasn't too bad but that was just the beginning making this change also meant that I now had two variables per player to save in the data store and that caused a lot of problems but I'll skip all the boring details what matters is that I did get it to work after a few hours and by that I mean that it was now midnight I felt bad for not adding that much new stuff for the day so I thought I'd try learning one last thing sound effects and uh yep it sure works one thing to note though is that you can only upload 10 sound effects a month which kind of sucks you do have unlimited access to the marketplace but put me down I can't take this please put me down what yeah it's a mixed bag anyhow before stopping for the day I finally gave the game some much needed sound effects have a listen all right the final day I will was starting to feel the strain of working on something 6 days in a row without taking a day off but hey if I want to be a game developer I'd better get used to it am I right anyway I wanted to spend the day adding as many features and as much polish as possible but after doing a quick multiplayer test I realized that data stores were still completely broken Bren and would cause various interesting bugs like having someone else's car show up on my UI somehow and then other bugs were just silly mistakes like here in the code that runs when you die your high score gets saved to the data store and if your score is higher than your high score your high score gets updated Can you spot the problem here well let's say you got a new high score and then died your current high score gets saved to the data store and then since your score is higher than your high score your high score gets updated so at that point if you were to quit the game and come back your high score would be lost you might have a mental image of a computer bug as being a small little math error that causes big problems but more often than not it's really just dumb things like this anyway after a long time of fixing similar bugs I finally got everything working correctly for real this time all I had to do was remove the part that wasn't working instead of fixing it okay now that everything worked I could finally start adding content and oh my God it's already 1: p.m. now with the limited time I had left I wanted to focus on diversifying the game play cuz as it is now every life is basically the same so my idea was to give the floor platform some random events using our good old friend tweening I can give the platform custom movements such as closing opening opening a lot tilting tilting but closed spinning moving side to side and my personal favorite bouncing I still had many ideas left like making a y element warn you about the upcoming event but unfortunately my time was up there's still quite a few things I wish I had learned but overall I think I'm happy with what I managed to make in only 7 Days oh and if you want to try the game out yourself I'll put a link to it in the description well before I knew it the Roblox learning week was over so what did I think of Roblox Studio well I liked it I thought it was really fun to use there were a few bumps along the road of course but overall Studio was really easy to learn now sure I already knew how to code and I have some Game Dev experience but Roblox Studio was the first time I ever successfully used an engine that's 3D multiplayer and only uses code cuz as a matter of fact most of my Game Dev experience actually comes from codeless engines now do I think Studio should be your first engine uh no I'd still recommend scratch but here's the thing in general most engines will have a trade-off between how easy it is to learn and how much power and freedom it gives you and I felt like Roblox gave you a pretty nice balance you're limited by the fact that you can only make games for Roblox but in exchange you're given a tool to easily make multiplayer games and by the way making a multiplayer game is really hard it's not as simple as clicking the make multiplayer button in your engine and on top of that hosting Game servers costs a lot of money yet the fact that Roblox will just give any anyone free server space at no costs that's really cool you shouldn't take that for granted okay so back to this graph real quick if your goal is to make a big 3D game but all you know is like scratch then I think Learning Studio could be a great way to ease the transition into bigger engines engines like oh I don't know Gau for example which incident the way gdau works with its node system is kind of similar to how Studio works with the whole parents child system I'm just saying lastly I'd like to quickly go over why I think Studio was so easy to learn mainly I'd say it's thanks to the official documentation This is How I Learned almost everything more than any tutorial and especially more than the AI assistant this is where I learned it all as long as you can like you know read and pay attention pay attention you can learn everything you'll ever need to know about Studio it's as easy as going on Google and typing Roblox than whatever you're trying to learn and usually it's the first link don't know how to use a search engine no problem just rightclick on any object and click help and heck in the code editor it'll constantly give you a short description of whatever you're typing and if you click the learn more button it'll send you straight to the documentation so you have no excuses Roblox is easy to learn and yeah I think Roblox studio is pretty fun however that's not quite the end of the story I'd be doing a disservice if I didn't also talk about Roblox itself so I quickly mentioned around the start of the video that Roblox has a lot of issues but there's one in particular that really bothers me here's the thing with Roblox for those who don't know Roblox has a premium currency called Roo that you can buy with real money and spend on in-game items and then as a developer you can add in-game purchases to your project and get a cut of the roox and if you're really successful you can become a Roblox partner and trade your roblo for real money and some people have gone actual millions of dollars doing that so chances are if you want to make a Roblox game it's because you just want to make some easy Roo but but here's my problem with that how do you think these developers made so much money by making really good highquality games and using honest business practices yeah right come on who am I kidding most likely it's by using the same kind of 30 tactics mobile games use to maximize profits like daily login bonuses limited time sale pay to win mechanics battle passes microtransactions loot boxes and of course gambling dang it dang it dang it dang it dang it ah yes selling gambling to Children a classic oh but it's not it's not real money it's fake in-game currency see it's not gambling yes ingame currency that you can buy with roblo which you can buy using real money I really think it's a shame that this is what Roblox is teaching to Young aspiring game developers to be greedy instead of wanting to make a fun experience and from what I've heard the Roblox algorithm seems to push games that make a lot of money which in turn makes the game more popular and thus makes more money regardless of if the game is actually good or not so if you want your game to be popular you don't have much of a choice or do you you know it doesn't have to be this way I don't think so instead of complaining that Roblox isn't what it used to be why don't we do something about it after all Roblox games aren't made by big companies they are made by people like you and me and what I hope that I've managed to show with this video is that making Roblox games is easy if I could learn to do that in a week imagine what you could do in like a month or two you know you could even have a couple of friends tag along thanks to the team create feature and when you play Roblox and you finally find a good game tell people about it share it to your friends support the Creator if you can you can also watch share and make videos about underrated Roblox games and if you know anyone that wastes their Precious roox on brain rot games try to convince them to maybe stop if we all do our part then maybe just maybe we can make Roblox a slightly better place and you know what if you you want to put a little donation option in your game that's fine if you can make a few roblo like that good for you that's awesome just don't do it just for the robo do it cuz it's fun all right but hey at the end of the day only one thing is for sure in life there's Roblox oh	28242	t	The content addresses high-intent beginner questions regarding the learning curve of Roblox Studio and its viability as a legitimate game engine for 3D multiplayer development.	{"Roblox Studio tutorial","learn Roblox game development","Roblox Studio for beginners","is Roblox a game engine","how to make Roblox games"}	2026-01-08 15:18:56.412798	\N	\N	[{"apis": ["BasePart.Position", "BasePart.Size", "BasePart.Orientation", "BasePart.CFrame"], "problem": "Basic 3D object manipulation including moving, scaling, and rotating parts", "category": "3D Modeling", "difficulty": "beginner", "automatable": false}, {"apis": ["InsertService", "Model"], "problem": "Integration of user-generated assets and models from the Toolbox", "category": "3D Modeling", "difficulty": "beginner", "automatable": true}, {"apis": ["Terrain:FillBlock", "Terrain:FillRegion", "Terrain:Editor"], "problem": "Environment creation using the smooth terrain system", "category": "Terrain", "difficulty": "beginner", "automatable": false}, {"apis": ["Team Create"], "problem": "Enabling real-time collaborative editing for multi-user development", "category": "Networking", "difficulty": "beginner", "automatable": false}, {"apis": ["RemoteEvent", "RemoteFunction", "Players", "RunService"], "problem": "Transitioning game logic from 2D single-player environments to 3D multiplayer networking", "category": "Networking", "difficulty": "intermediate", "automatable": false}, {"apis": ["Model:ScaleTo", "BasePart.Size"], "problem": "Programmatic scaling of massive character models and environmental geometry", "category": "3D Mo